Strengthens our thesis Impact to our thesis
Modest shortfall Financial results versus consensus
Modest revision lower Direction of next 12- month consensus EPS
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research
2Q25 NP missed consensus estimates, we think; Container shipping segment profit dropped by Rmb6.6bn (- 56%) QoQ, more significant vs. OOIL (- 43% QoQ).
Interim div \(50\%\) payout was in line.
We see a continued normalization in earnings in 2H25, which could also bring down forward dividends, potentially putting pressure on valuation.
CSH reported 1H25 NP Rmb17.5bn, tracking \(56\%\) of 2025 MSE of Rmb31.6bn. Implied 2Q25 NP - 42% YoY.

Segment profit was Rmb5.2bn in 2Q25, vs. Rmb11.8bn in 1Q25. COSCO Shipping Lines 1H25 NP dipped \(2\%\) YoY (in US\$ terms), in contrast to \(15\%\) YoY NP increase for OOIL. Freight rate declines were meaningful on Transpacific (- 14% YoY) and Asia- Europe (- 23% YoY) routes in 2Q25. 2Q25 shipping volume \(+5.7\%\) YoY to 6.8mn TEUs, \(+5.4\%\) YoY on intl routes.
OCF \(+14\%\) YoY to Rmb26bn, capex - 18% YoY to Rmb9.8bn, in 1H25. The company recorded Rmb7bn lease payment in financing CF 1H25.
Interim dividend: of Rmb0.56 per share, inline \(\sim 50\%\) payout ratio, \(4.2\%\) yield on Hshare close, and \(3.50\%\) on A- share close.
MORGAN STANLEY ASIA LIMITED+
Qianlei Fan, CFA Equity Analyst
Qianlei Fan/omorganstanley.com

2025e P/B, probability- weighted \(15\%\) bull, \(70\%\) base, \(15\%\) bear. We see equal probabilities of the upside supported by global trade recovery and long- lasting supply chain disruptions, and the downside given the current unfavorable supply- demand outlook. Target P/Bs: 1.0x bull (0.3x SD below its historical mean since listing), 0.6x base (0.8x SD below its historical mean since listing), and 0.3x bear (1.2x SD below historical mean since listing).
Spot market turnaround. Better- than- expected earnings distribution. Red Sea disruption lasting for longer than expected. Aggressive share repurchases.

Global trade drops amid macro headwinds and potential US tariffs hikes. A significant increase in fuel prices. Failure of segment capacity discipline. Cost inflation if US 301 section investigation implemented.
